Pittsburgh 311 call analysis

Brian Bowling

August 23, 2018

People contact Pittsburghs 311 center to raise concerns about everything from cracked sidewalks to dangerous buildings.

About 42 percent of the 311 calls made in Pittsburgh concern road and street issues such as potholes, obstructions, etc. The next two largest categories are neighborhood issues such as derelict buildings and overgrown lots and garbage and litter issues.

Heres a list of the top 10 categories:

category requests pct_total
Road/Street Issues 145,445 42.2
Neighborhood Issues 34,140 9.9
Garbage and Litter Issues 30,874 9
Building Maintenance 20,583 6
Parks Issues 18,703 5.4
Utility Issues 14,151 4.1
Parking 12,584 3.7
Public Safety 12,330 3.6
Tree Issues 10,080 2.9
Construction Issues 7,325 2.1

In terms of specific issues, potholes are the most frequent reason people contact the 311 Center. Heres a list of the top 10 issues:

request_type requests pct_total
potholes 76,018 22.1
weeds/debris 22,280 6.5
litter 21,640 6.3
snow/ice removal 18,752 5.4
traffic 12,774 3.7
building maintenance 11,194 3.3
replace/repair a sign 10,500 3
leak 9,280 2.7
overgrowth 8,554 2.5
refuse violations 6,789 2

From May 2015 to July 2018, the 311 center has been contacted 344,400 times about issues within the citys boundaries. The median number of 311 calls has gone from 245 per day in 2015 to 469 per day so far in 2018.

The volume of requests follow a seasonal pattern with snow/ice removal driving up the 311 calls in winter months followed by an even higher number of pothole calls when things start thawing out.

Heres a map showing the total requests and the 2018 median monthly requests by neighborhood.

Heres a map showing the total call per person using each neighborhoods estimated daytime population as the denominator. The daytime population was calculated using 2016 American Community Survey population estimates and Census Bureau estimates of the number of jobs and employed residents in each area. The basic formula is area population + (workers with jobs in the area - residents in the area who have jobs). This accounts for people who live outside the area but work in the area as well as residents who work outside of the area.
